ownedComment.body:
Decision Architect consists of five views.
  • Decision detail view (double-click on a decision)
  • Decision relationship view (add new diagram)
  • Decision chronology view (generate from the add-in's context menu)
  • Decision forces view (add new diagram)
  • Decision stakeholder involvement view (add new diagram)

The decision forces view identifies the impact of forces on decisions. A force is any aspect that influenced the architect when making the decisions out of multiple alternatives, such as requirements , qualities or experience. The decision forces view is a table that lists forces on the vertical dimension and decisions on the horizontal dimension.

The decision relationship view illustrates dependencies between decisions and their current state (e.g. idea, decided, rejected). Examples of relationships between decisions are caused by, replaces or is alternative for, e.g. MySQL replaces SQLite.

The detail view is the default dialog that is shown when a decision has been selected.This view provides detailed information about a single decision including its rationale. Furthermore, does the view aggregate information from other viewpoints, such as forces, relations, traces or stakeholders.

The stakeholder involvement view explains the responsibilities of specific stakeholders in the decision-making process. It shows decisions, actions, and stakeholders involved within one architecture iteration.

Decision States and Colors
  • Challenged decisions are red to emphasize that this decision represents an unsolved problem and requires further discussion.
  • Discarded or rejected decisions are displayed in an unobtrusive gray.
  • Ideas resemble the bright yellow of a light bulb.
  • Tentative mean that a decision is seriously considered but has not been decided yet. Therefore, it is displayed in a light blue.
  • Decided and approved decisions are visualized in a gradient from light to dark green to illustrate the increasing certainty of a decision. A decided state reflects the current position of the architect, while an approved state means that the decision has been confirmed, e.g., during a review meeting.
The decision chronology view shows the evolution of decisions over time.
